  <ul>
    <li>Spending time with my family - we love to be outdoors when the weather is nice.</li>
    <li>Creating things in the home recording studio.</li>
    <li>Building PCs with the kids.</li>
    <li>Constantly learning through hands-on experimentation — diving into new open-source projects, spinning up tools in my homelab, and breaking things just to figure out how they really work.</li>
    <li>Working on cars, constantly talking about Tesla.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id='homelab'>HomeLab Environment</h2>
  I run a full UniFi ecosystem for networking and management. The top patch panel handles all 1 Gb devices plus a handful of 2.5 Gb clients. Directly below it sits my 10 Gb switch, dedicated to high-bandwidth gear: the Dell R730xd, UniFi UNAS Pro, and a few UniFi U7 Pro XG access points with 10 Gb uplinks. Yes, it’s complete overkill.

  <Collapse title='Click to see HomeLab Rack - Front'><img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/pipitonelabs/k8s-gitops/main/docs/assets/rack-front.jpg" alt="Rack front view"></Collapse>

  In the back of the rack are three Minisforum MS-01 mini-PCs serving as my Kubernetes cluster nodes. Each runs both control-plane and worker roles for a fully HA control plane, and they’re all mounted in custom 3D-printed 1U rack ears.

  <Collapse title='Click to see HomeLab Rack - Rear'><img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/pipitonelabs/k8s-gitops/main/docs/assets/rack-rear.jpg" alt="Rack rear view"></Collapse>

  Feel free to check out my <a href='https://github.com/pipitonelabs/k8s-gitops' target='_blank'>k8s-gitops</a> repo where you can see how I'm utilizing a GitOps approach with <a href='https://fluxcd.io/' target='_blank'>Flux</a> and GitHub Actions for Kubernetes cluster and application management.

